        <h2>Terms of Service</h2>
        <p class="info-meta">Last updated: 2026-05-22</p>

        <p>By using Json-Pi (the "Service"), you agree to these terms. If you do not agree, please do not use the Service.</p>

        <h3>1. Use of the Service</h3>
        <p>Json-Pi is provided free of charge for personal and commercial use. You may use it to process your own data or data you have permission to process. You may not use it for anything illegal, abusive, or that violates third-party rights.</p>

        <h3>2. No warranty</h3>
        <p>The Service is provided "as is" without warranty of any kind, express or implied. We make no guarantees about availability, accuracy, fitness for purpose, or that the output will be error-free.</p>

        <h3>3. Limitation of liability</h3>
        <p>To the maximum extent permitted by law, the developer and contributors are not liable for any damages — direct, indirect, incidental, or consequential — arising from your use of the Service, including loss of data, business interruption, or any other commercial damages.</p>

        <h3>4. Your data</h3>
        <p>Json-Pi processes your data locally in your browser. We do not collect, store, or transmit your documents unless you explicitly use the Developer API endpoints — in which case the data is processed and immediately returned, not retained. Contact form submissions are stored to deliver your message and may be retained indefinitely.</p>

        <h3>5. Intellectual property</h3>
        <p>The Json-Pi application is owned by Sarim Sikander. Third-party libraries used by Json-Pi remain the property of their respective owners and are used under their open-source licenses.</p>

